Title : Casa Valentina
Text : {{italic title}}
[[File:Jiuuu.jpg|thumb|Casa Valentina Playbill]]
'''''Casa Valentina''''' is a play written by [[Harvey Fierstein]] which premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in April 2014 and opened in London in September 2015. It tells the story of men who spend weekends at a resort in the Catskill mountains, dressed as women.

==Background==
The play was suggested by the book ''Casa Susanna'', written by Michel Hurst and Robert Swope, which collected photographs from a cross-dressing resort [[Casa Susanna|of the same name]].<ref>Purcell, Carey. [http://www.playbill.com/article/mtc-to-present-broadway-world-premiere-of-harvey-fiersteins-casa-valentina-com-209289# "MTC To Present Broadway World Premiere of Harvey Fierstein's ''Casa Valentina''"] Playbill, September 9, 2013, accessed May 15, 2016</ref>

==Productions==
''Casa Valentina'' premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] at the [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] in a [[Manhattan Theatre Club]] production on April 1, 2014 in previews, officially on April 23, 2014. Directed by [[Joe Mantello]], the cast featured [[Patrick Page]] (George/Valentina), [[Gabriel Ebert]] (Jonathon/Miranda), [[John Cullum]] (Terry), [[Reed Birney]] (Charlotte), Tom McGowan (Bessie), [[Larry Pine]] (The Judge/Amy) and [[Mare Winningham]] (Rita).<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/article/the-verdict-critics-review-harvey-fiersteins-new-broadway-play-casa-valentina-com-217574# "The Verdict: Critics Review Harvey Fierstein's New Broadway Play ''Casa Valentina''"] Playbill, April 24, 2014</ref> Scenic design was by [[Scott Pask]], costumes by Rita Ryack and lighting by Justin Townsend.<ref>Purcell, Carey. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/190294-Harvey-Fiersteins-Casa-Valentina-Starring-Patrick-Page-John-Cullum-and-Gabriel-Ebert-Opens-on-Broadway "Harvey Fierstein's ''Casa Valentina'', Starring Patrick Page, John Cullum and Gabriel Ebert, Opens on Broadway"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423231011/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/190294-Harvey-Fiersteins-Casa-Valentina-Starring-Patrick-Page-John-Cullum-and-Gabriel-Ebert-Opens-on-Broadway |date=April 23, 2014 }} Playbill, April 23, 2014</ref> The play had music by Fitz Patton, with [[Christopher Gattelli]] as dance consultant.<ref name=vault>[http://www.playbill.com/production/casa-valentina-samuel-j-friedman-theatre-vault-0000014040 "''Casa Valentina'' Listing"] Playbill, accessed May 12, 2016</ref> The play closed on June 29, 2014 after 79 performances and 24 previews.<ref name=vault/>
<ref>Purcell, Carey. [http://www.playbill.com/article/harvey-fiersteins-casa-valentina-closes-its-doors-june-29-com-322948# "Harvey Fierstein's ''Casa Valentina'' Closes Its Doors June 29"] Playbill, June 29, 2014</ref>

The play made its London debut at the [[Southwark Playhouse]] on September 10, 2015 in previews, running through October 10. Directed by Luke Sheppard, the cast featured [[Tamsin Carroll]] (Rita), Ben Deery (Miranda), Charlie Hayes (Eleanor), Bruce Montague (Terry), Robert Morgan (Amy), Matt Rixon (Bessie), Ashley Robinson (Gloria), Gareth Snook (Charlotte) and Edward Wolstenholme (Valentina).<ref>Shenton, Mark. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/london-premiere-of-harvey-fiersteins-casa-valentina-begins-tonight-361509# "London Premiere of Harvey Fierstein's ''Casa Valentina'' Begins Tonight"] Playbill, September 10, 2015</ref><ref>Caird, Joe. [http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/reviews/casa-valentina-southwark-playhouse_38749.html "''Casa Valentina'' (Southwark Playhouse)"] whatsonstage.com,17 September 2015</ref>

The play will be making its Chicago debut with Pride Films and Plays in August 2019.<ref>Hookey, Sarah. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/chicago/article/Pride-Films-and-Plays-Announces-Full-Cast-for-Harvey-Fiersteins-CASA-VALENTINA-20190515 "Pride Films and Plays Announces Full Cast for Harvey Fierstein's Casa Valentina"] broadwayworld.com, 15 May 2019</ref>

==Plot==
Casa Valentina is a small hotel in the resort area of the [[Catskill Mountains]] in New York. In the early 1960s, Casa Valentina has, as guests, heterosexual men who dress and act as women. They are faced with a decision whether to become an official organization.

==Critical reception==
The reviewer for ''theatermania'' wrote that ''Casa Valentina'' is "far and away the best new play of the season."<ref>Gordon, David. [http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/reviews/04-2014/casa-valentina_68347.html "Reviews. 'Casa Valentina'"] theatermania.com, April 23, 2014</ref>

